Mithril Heart Brigade</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/unaginatakuroshio.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Naginata Kuroshio</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC=http://www.rose-hulman.edu/~acuffnd/Reference/icon1.gif BORDER=0 HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Master of The Elements</span><br>  Posts: 86<br> <font color=#333333>(12/21/00 5:05:17 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerrants.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=46.topic&index=6>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Has this  happened to anyone else?</span><hr size=1> I just want to throw this in for what it's worth... Not trying to make anyone mad, just trying to say something to demonstrate that I'm definately aware of what Ommundan is talking about...<br>
<br>
I like to think of it this way - Druids are the utility class of the game.  They can Heal, snare, nuke, DoT, occasionally even pull.  Basically, if your group is short something, and you get a druid, chances are they can do at least a half-assed job at it<br>
<br>
Much in the same way, Mages are the utility class of the casters - we can nuke, we can tank (not directly, of course), we can make the cleric more efficient (At the cost of us doing anything else productive), we can damage shield with the best of em... We can do just about anything but heal (and if we're being the tank, we can even do that, sort of).<br>
<br>
Here's a good example - I was in a solid group in the Hole last night, we didn't go far in, but here's what we had - <br>
2 paladins, a cleric, an enchanter, a shaman, and myself.  It's situations like this where mage flexibility really makes us the keystone of a group.  Most of the time, I played the &quot;mage&quot; - damage shielding, sending the pet in to do his thing, and malising so that the pet's stuns would actually do something productive.  (when things are even to you, this really helps the tanks take less damage - your cleric will thank you!)  There were times, however, when we'd get a bad pull right after the enc finished buffing people and go oom.  Then, it became my job to go into solo mode, and kill off something quickly, so the group could concentrate it's energy elsewhere.  Another time, we pulled a yellow mudthingie (wait, that's about everything in the hole...)  and I had to play the wizzie - coordinating my nuke with the paladins' stuns, and dumping basically everything I had in an attempt to take it down, so that the cleric would have mana to let the tanks take down the other 2 things that were waiting in the wings mezzed.  <br>
<br>
The point here isn't that people who tell you you need to do something different are wrong - often times, someone will suggest something different, like letting the shaman malise so that I can toss an extra nuke around... it's when people assume that I don't know what I'm doing, and order me, not ask me, to change it.  I mean, I'm level 53.  I didn't get there by being a moron (although there are some of those around...).  Unless you soloed your entire life or bought your character on ebay, by the time you're 50+ you should have an idea of what your role(s) are in a group.  I could understand someone ordering me to change what I was doing if I was doing stupid things and getting the group in trouble... but the fact is that in the group that I mentioned in the previous post, the reason I think the wizzie wanted me to nuke more was because most fights went like this:<br>
<br>
1) Puller yells &quot;incoming&quot;<br>
2) tanks do their thing<br>
3) Debuffs/DoT's go on<br>
4) Wizzie nukes<br>
5) Wizzie nukes<br>
6) Wizzie attempts to bludgeon the mob's fists to death with his face<br>
7) Mage pet is the only tank left on the mob, thanks to the wizzies pingpong skills, and a well-timed root lets the wizzie escape with his life<br>
