Sheesh... I'll never understand why people put so much value in mod rods.  If a cleric is doing their job, and a tank is doing their job, clerics will rarely be in a position to need them.<br>
<br>
Yeah, after massive buffing (symbol, hero, etc.) giving a cleric rods helps us get started again.  And after a rez, same thing.  But during the fastest, hardest pulling I have been in so far in a regular exp group (OS - ilis jail, D2, chef, king) it's pretty rare that a cleric is asking for these.  When things go wrong, sure that's a case too, but that's not too often.  Are they helpful?  Sure, just not needed that often.  If we didn't have them it would just mean once in a while a tiny bit more down time for medding.  Big whoop.<br>
<br>
But back to the main point.  Post-55, most people who have made it that far (and aren't eBay'd) know how to play their class.  And most people know that most people know how to play their class, and rarely if ever make suggestions.  Except to say 'hey mage, want me to do DS?' in response to me being low on mana, or 'hey cleric, I'll pick up small heals for a bit' in response to a cleric being low on mana.<br>
<br>
If someone makes a suggestion, if they have played a mage before, I'll listen to learn.  Or if it's a general group tactic change, then I really want to listen so I can learn, especially if it's in an area where I haven't been before.  But if it's just ignorance, then it's silly and I just ignore it, perhaps saying 'thank you for the advice' or something else non-committal.<br>
